if (!file.exists("met_all.gz"))
  download.file(
    url = "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/USCbiostats/data-science-data/master/02_met/met_all.gz",
    destfile = "met_all.gz",
    method   = "libcurl",
    timeout  = 60
    )
met <- data.table::fread("met_all.gz")

2

met <- met[temp > -17] [elev == 9999.0, elev := NA]

met[, week := week(as.Date(paste(year, month, day, sep = "-")))]

met <- met[week == min(week, na.rm = TRUE)]

met_avg <- met[,.(temp=mean(temp,na.rm=TRUE), rh=mean(rh,na.rm=TRUE),
                  wind.sp=mean(wind.sp,na.rm=TRUE),
                vis.dist=mean(vis.dist,na.rm=TRUE),
                dew.point=mean(dew.point, na.rm=TRUE),
                lat=mean(lat), lon=mean(lon),
                elev=mean(elev,na.rm=TRUE)), by="USAFID"]

met_avg$region <- ifelse(met_avg$lon > -98 & met_avg$lat >39.71, "north east",
                         ifelse(met_avg$lon > -98 & 
                                  met_avg$lat < 39.71, "south east",
                                ifelse(met_avg$lon < -98 & met_avg$lat >39.71, 
                                       "north west", "south west")))

met_avg$elev_cat <- ifelse(met_avg$elev> 252, "high", "low")

met_avg %>%
  filter(!(dew.point %in% NA)) %>%
ggplot()+
  geom_violin(mapping = aes(y=dew.point, x=1)) +
  facet_wrap(~region, nrow=2)

The violin plot for wind speed varies by region where wind speeds for the northeast and southeast tend to be lower in comparison to the southwest and northwest regions, based on the widths. It is interesting to note that the violin plot for the wind speed in the north east region most likely has a lot of outliers given the long tail. For dew points, the violin plot shows relatively consistent dew points for the north east and south east regions. However, for the southwest and the northwest regions, the distribution of dew points vary from high to low, especially for the north west region which shows a varied density by observing its width.

met_avg %>%
filter(!is.na(dew.point) & !is.na(wind.sp)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x=dew.point, y=rh, color=region))+
  geom_jitter() +
  stat_smooth(method=lm)
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

The scatter plot demonstrates a somewhat positive relationship between dew point and wind speed across all regions. All regional regression lines show increasing slopes, indicating that as dew point increases, relative humidity increases too. The relationship appears strongest in the northwest region, while the south east region shows a slower, gradual increase.

5

met_avg %>%
filter(!(elev_cat %in% NA)) %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x=elev_cat,fill=region), position = "dodge") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "PRGn") +
  labs(title = "Number of weather stations by elevation category and region",
       x="Elevation Category", y="Count") +
  theme_bw()

The bar chart reveals significant differences in weather station distribution across regions and elevation categories. The southeast region has the highest number of stations overall, particularly concentrated at lower elevations. The northwest region shows more stations at high elevations compared to low elevations, which likely reflects the presence of geographic landmarks (i.e., more mountain range) in that particular region. This distribution pattern suggests that the southeast is more vulnerable to extreme weather events, which calls for the need of more weather stations for them.

The region with the highest mean dew point (approximately 21C), indicating its proximity to bodies of water, more specifically, warm, moist waters of the Gulf of Mexico and the Atlantic Ocean. The northwest region displays the lowest mean dew point at around 12C, suggesting that the air is often cold and cold air canât hold as much moisture. The error bars reveal that northwest and southwest regions has the most variable conditions, while the southeast region shows the least variable conditions.

Regional differences in wind speed are different compared to dew point patterns. The southwest region shows higher mean wind speeds at just above 3 m/s with large variability, indicating there is less precision in the measuring for wind speeds. The southeast and northeast regions display lower mean wind speeds suggesting stable atmospheric conditions.

met_avg2 <- met_avg[!is.na(rh)]

top10 <- met_avg2[rank(-rh) <= 10]

rh_pal = colorNumeric(c('blue','purple','red'), domain = met_avg2$rh)

leaflet(met_avg2) %>%
  addProviderTiles('OpenStreetMap') %>%
  addCircles(lat=~lat, lng=~lon, color=~rh_pal(rh),
             label=~paste0(round(rh,2), ' rh'), opacity=1,fillOpacity = 1, radius = 500) %>%
  addMarkers(lat=~lat, lng=~lon, label=~paste0(round(rh,2), ' rh'), data = top10) %>%
  addLegend('bottomleft',pal=rh_pal, values=met_avg2$rh,
            title="Relative Humidity", opacity = 1)

The relative humidity map reveals a clear, gradual increase gradient across the United States. The eastern regions show higher humidity values, represented by purple and red colors. The central region displays a mid-range humidity levels, while the western regions exhibit low humidity values, with the exception of the western costal region. Majority of the top 10 highest relative humidity locations are predominantly located near bodies of water, which reflects the influence of moisture deriving from the ocean. This pattern demonstrates how wind speed and dew point factors affect regional humidity distributions.
